Introduction¶

The Soccer dataset consists mainly of three main data groups:

  1. Data about home and away teams' scored goals and betting odds data for +25,000 matches
  2. Data about players' names, birthday, height and weight with attributes sourced from EA Sports' FIFA video game series
  3. Data about teams' long and short names with attributes also sourced from FIFA, including the weekly updates

We will load these data sources in the next section from SQLite database and group them as mentioned above.

In [1]:
# import needed packages
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sqlalchemy import create_engine
In [2]:
# Create SQLAlchemy Engine to connect to Soccer sqlite database
engine = create_engine('sqlite:///database.sqlite')

Now we have created the three main data groups which we can use to help us answer the following questions:

  • Which players had the highest penalties' ratings of all time?
  • What team's attributes lead to the most victories?
  • What teams improved the most over the time period?

Exploring Match Data¶

We can see from Matches data that there is no an easy way or single column that can inform us what is the final result of the match? Which team won the home or away team? Or if the match ended with a draw for both teams?

So, next we will create two columns for home and away teams to record in them the final result for each whether: Win, Lose or Draw. This will be done through comparison queries between columns home_team_goal and away_team_goal as follows.

In [49]:
# Create "home_team_result" column to carry the final match result for the home team
df_match['home_team_result'] = ["Win" if match.home_team_goal > match.away_team_goal else "Lose" if match.home_team_goal < match.away_team_goal else "Draw" for match in df_match.itertuples()]
# Create "away_team_result" column to carry the final match result for the home team
df_match['away_team_result'] = ["Win" if match.away_team_goal > match.home_team_goal else "Lose" if match.away_team_goal < match.home_team_goal else "Draw" for match in df_match.itertuples()]

Exploring Team Attributes Data¶

The Team's data has no single attribute to indicate how good a team is, as the overall_rating in the player's. So, we will try to create this indicator based on the "chance creation" attributes by assuming the following:

chanceCreationTotal = chanceCreationPassing + chanceCreationCrossing + chanceCreationShooting
In [54]:
def chanceCreationList(team_attributes_dataframe):
    # Create empty list
    total_chance_creation_list = []
    # Loop over team attributes dataframe to calculate total chance creation for each team
    for team_attributes in team_attributes_dataframe.itertuples():
        # Caculate total chance creation by the summation formula
        total_chance_creation = team_attributes.chanceCreationPassing + team_attributes.chanceCreationCrossing \
                                + team_attributes.chanceCreationShooting
        # Append the calculate value to the list
        total_chance_creation_list.append(total_chance_creation)
    # Return the created full list

What teams improved the most over the time period?¶

We can calculate the team's improvement as the difference between the latest chanceCreationTotal and the oldest one by date. So that the higher the difference is the better the improvement!

In [64]:
def calculateTeamsImprovement(threshold=None):
    # Create empty list to hold teams' improvement values
    chance_creation_improvement_list = []
    # Create empty list to hold improved teams above the threshold
    most_improved_teams = []
    # Loop over teams' groups to calculate teams' improvement values
    for name, group in df_team_attributes.groupby('team_long_name'):
        # Calculate improvement by substracting oldest "total chance creation" from the lastest one by date
        chance_creation_improvement_list.append(group['chanceCreationTotal'].iloc[-1] - group['chanceCreationTotal'].iloc[0])
        # Add the team group to the improved teams list if the improvement is greater than the threshold
        if threshold != None and chance_creation_improvement_list[-1] >= threshold:
            most_improved_teams.append((name, group))
    # Sort the improvement values descendingly
    chance_creation_improvement_list.sort(reverse=True)
    # Convert list to numpy array to easily apply optimized vectorization methods
    chance_creation_improvement_list = np.array(chance_creation_improvement_list)
    # Return the created lists
    return chance_creation_improvement_list, most_improved_teams

Results (Our data suggest the following)¶

  1. To attain most victories your need to have the following attributes:
    • Balanced buid-up speed
    • Little build-up play dribbling
    • Short build-up play passing
    • Free form build-up play positioning
    • Normal chance creation passing
    • Little chance creation crossing
    • Normal chance creation shooting
    • Free form chance creation positioning
    • Medium defence pressure
    • Press defence aggression
    • Normal defence team width
    • Cover defence defender line
  2. Teams with most victories are not the most improving over time.
  3. Most of the teams could preserve a close away winning rank to their home one.
  4. The max penalties rating is only achieved by a single player.

Limitations (There are a couple of limitations with our data)¶

  1. Some of player's and team's data were missing and we needed to fill numerical values by mean and categorical by mode.
  2. Teams improvement values' calculation is based on the summation of the chance creation values which may not be the best indicator of improvement.
  3. Highest penalties ratings were calculated as the absolute maximum regardless of the time period they were achieved at.
  4. Teams and players attributes are not sampled at the same dates or even with the same number of weeks.
